---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import Header from '../components/Header.astro';
import BrandMark from '../components/BrandMark.astro';
import Footer from '../components/Footer.astro';
---
<BaseLayout>
  <Header>
    <BrandMark slot="mark" />
  </Header>

  <main>
    <section class="section hero-section">
      <div class="shell surface-dark pad hero-card">
        <div class="hero-copy">
          <div class="meta-label">Why Aster</div>
          <h1 class="page-hero-title">Address-first RPC no longer matches the systems we actually build.</h1>
          <p class="page-copy">
            gRPC assumes stable hostnames, central load balancers, and trust delegated to infrastructure.
            That model breaks in edge deployments, NAT-heavy environments, mobile topologies, and
            multi-runtime AI systems. Aster starts from cryptographic identity, portable contracts,
            and transport that tolerates real-world paths.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="hero-side">
          <div class="note-card">
            <div class="meta-label">Core thesis</div>
            <p>Identities matter more than addresses. Contracts are portable artifacts. Services operate across real-world networks.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section">
      <div class="shell surface-light-wrap">
        <div class="surface-light pad">
          <div class="section-head">
            <div>
              <div class="meta-label">What Aster is</div>
               <h2 class="page-section-title">An identity-first distributed systems substrate.</h2>
            </div>
             <p class="page-copy">
              Aster composes three independent layers into one coherent system: iroh QUIC for
              identity-first transport, Apache Fory for high-performance cross-language
              serialization, and language-native contracts with content-addressed identity.
            </p>
          </div>
          <div class="grid grid-3">
            <article class="card light-card">
              <div class="meta-label">Transport</div>
               <h3 class="page-card-title">Identity is the connection</h3>
               <p class="page-card-copy">Peers dial by ed25519 public key over iroh QUIC. NAT traversal via hole-punching with relay fallback. No hostname, no port, no DNS.</p>
            </article>
            <article class="card light-card">
              <div class="meta-label">Contract</div>
               <h3 class="page-card-title">Contracts have real identity</h3>
               <p class="page-card-copy">Each service contract has a BLAKE3 content hash. The same <code>contract_id</code> resolves to the same interface across every language runtime.</p>
            </article>
            <article class="card light-card">
              <div class="meta-label">Runtime</div>
               <h3 class="page-card-title">Cross-language without flattening languages</h3>
               <p class="page-card-copy">Python uses <code>@service</code> and <code>@rpc</code> decorators. Rust, JVM, Go, and .NET will use their own native idioms. Same wire protocol, same contract_id.</p>
            </article>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section">
      <div class="shell surface-dark pad">
        <div class="section-head dark">
          <div>
            <div class="meta-label">What Aster is optimizing for</div>
             <h2 class="page-section-title">Reachability, portability, explicit trust, and runtime dignity.</h2>
          </div>
           <p class="page-copy">
            Aster is not competing with gRPC on ecosystem maturity. It provides a better
            foundation for systems where peers move, trust cannot be implicit, sessions are
            stateful, and the network does not behave like a datacenter diagram.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="grid grid-2">
          <article class="card dark-card">
            <div class="meta-label">Optimization 01</div>
             <h3 class="page-card-title">Built for real networks</h3>
             <p class="page-card-copy">iroh QUIC handles hole-punching, relay fallback, and connection continuity across IP changes. No ingress controller, no service mesh sidecar, no static addressing.</p>
          </article>
          <article class="card dark-card">
            <div class="meta-label">Optimization 02</div>
             <h3 class="page-card-title">Trust as structure</h3>
             <p class="page-card-copy">Four-gate authorization: connection, admission, service, method. Offline root key signs enrollment credentials with expiry. Consumer admission via policy or one-time-token. No external auth provider required.</p>
          </article>
          <article class="card dark-card">
            <div class="meta-label">Optimization 03</div>
             <h3 class="page-card-title">Portable contract truth</h3>
             <p class="page-card-copy">Contracts are BLAKE3-hashed artifacts published to a decentralised registry built on iroh-docs, iroh-blobs, and iroh-gossip. The same contract_id means the same interface everywhere.</p>
          </article>
          <article class="card dark-card">
            <div class="meta-label">Optimization 04</div>
             <h3 class="page-card-title">Session-shaped interactions</h3>
             <p class="page-card-copy">Session-scoped services (<code>scoped='stream'</code>) maintain state across sequential calls within a single QUIC stream. In-band cancellation. All four streaming patterns: unary, server, client, bidirectional.</p>
          </article>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section">
      <div class="shell surface-light-wrap">
        <div class="surface-light pad">
          <div class="section-head">
            <div>
              <div class="meta-label">Aster in context</div>
               <h2 class=”page-section-title”>Not “gRPC but faster.” Not a blockchain product. Not a mesh rebrand.</h2>
            </div>
             <p class=”page-copy”>
              Aster is greenfield and honest about that. It is pre-release (0.1-alpha), Python-first,
              and deliberately early. The tradeoff is intentional: less ecosystem maturity today
              in exchange for a model that better fits identity-first, mixed-topology distributed
              systems where trust, mobility, and cross-language interop are structural concerns.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>
  </main>

  <Footer />
</BaseLayout>

<style>
  .pad { padding: 26px; }
  .hero-section { padding-top: 24px; }
  .hero-card, .section-head, .hero-copy { display: grid; gap: 18px; }
  .hero-card { grid-template-columns: minmax(0, 1.3fr) 260px; align-items: end; }
  .hero-copy h1, .section-head h2 { max-width: 12ch; }
  .hero-copy p { color: var(--mist); }
  .section-head { grid-template-columns: minmax(0, 1.1fr) minmax(280px, 0.9fr); margin-bottom: 22px; align-items: end; }
  .section-head p { color: var(--ink-soft); }
  .section-head.dark h2 { color: var(--cloud-strong); }
  .section-head.dark p { color: var(--mist); }
  .grid { display: grid; gap: 16px; }
  .grid-2 { grid-template-columns: repeat(2, minmax(0, 1fr)); }
  .grid-3 { grid-template-columns: repeat(3, minmax(0, 1fr)); }
  .card { border-radius: var(--radius-lg); padding: 18px; }
  .dark-card { border: 1px solid rgba(163, 178, 196, 0.1); background: rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.025); }
  .light-card, .note-card { border: 1px solid rgba(25, 37, 51, 0.1); background: rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.72); }
  .note-card { border-radius: var(--radius-lg); padding: 16px; }
  .meta-label { margin-bottom: 10px; font-size: 11px; line-height: 1.2; letter-spacing: 0.12em; text-transform: uppercase; }
  .card h3, .note-card p { margin: 0; }
  .dark-card h3 { color: var(--cloud-strong); }
  .light-card h3, .note-card p { color: var(--ink); }
  .dark-card p { color: var(--mist); }
  .light-card p { color: var(--ink-soft); }
  @media (max-width: 960px) {
    .hero-card, .section-head, .grid-2, .grid-3 { grid-template-columns: 1fr; }
    .pad { padding: 22px; }
  }
</style>
